{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-tsx","path":"/blog/3d-modeling-as-a-developer","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>As a developer, 3d modeling was something that I had always wanted to try since it was something that I needed to visualize the final product or to create prototypes in my DIY projects. For a long time I've been searching for a perfect CAD, but none of them were ideal for me.\nDuring one of my talks with a colleague of mine, he mentioned something about TinkerCAD, Fusion360 and OpenSCAD. The last one immediately got my attention as it had \"open\" in its name. I asked him to elaborate on that but \"that's geeky stuff\" was all that he said. I've decided then to look it up since I had a feeling that it might be something for me...</p>\n<h1>What's OpenSCAD</h1>\n<p>OpenSCAD is a small (approx. 25 MB) but powerful CAD that lets us design using it's own language. Its design is very simple and splits into 3 areas.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Editor</li>\n<li>Preview</li>\n<li>Console</li>\n</ol>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/263f4/screen1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 60.810810810810814%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 1\"\n        title=\"Screen 1\"\n        src=\"/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/fcda8/screen1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/12f09/screen1.png 148w,\n/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/e4a3f/screen1.png 295w,\n/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/fcda8/screen1.png 590w,\n/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/efc66/screen1.png 885w,\n/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/c83ae/screen1.png 1180w,\n/static/304a3a2dcd00dd3785656c96af0590f7/263f4/screen1.png 1996w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p>The best in openSCAD is its simplicity. All you need to know are a few shapes and functions, and that's all. This <a href=\"http://www.openscad.org/cheatsheet/\">cheat sheet</a> might come in handy as all the important knowledge is included in it.</p>\n<h1>How it works</h1>\n<p>Nearly everything can be created with functions.\nSyntax tree looks mostly like this:</p>\n<pre><code>object();\nvariable = value;\noperator() action();\noperator() {\n    action();\n    action();\n}\noperator() operator() {\n    action();\n    action();\n}\noperator() {\n    operator() action();\n    operator() {\n        action();\n        action();\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>For example, if we want to create a cylinder, we just have to call <code>cylinder(h,r|d,center)</code>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>h</code> is height</li>\n<li><code>r</code> is radius</li>\n<li><code>d</code> is diameter</li>\n</ul>\n<pre><code>cylinder(h=2, r=5);\n</code></pre>\n<p><code>center</code> parameter is not obligatory. It moves center of our shape to [0,0,0].</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/195c1075c19fda609d566da5c9dfac0c/3d84d/screen2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 79.72972972972973%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 2\"\n        title=\"Screen 2\"\n        src=\"/static/195c1075c19fda609d566da5c9dfac0c/fcda8/screen2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/195c1075c19fda609d566da5c9dfac0c/12f09/screen2.png 148w,\n/static/195c1075c19fda609d566da5c9dfac0c/e4a3f/screen2.png 295w,\n/static/195c1075c19fda609d566da5c9dfac0c/fcda8/screen2.png 590w,\n/static/195c1075c19fda609d566da5c9dfac0c/3d84d/screen2.png 628w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>You should name all the parameters. If you don't, it's more likely that you will make a mistake. If you called a previous function with two parameters but without names: <code>cylinder(2, 5);</code>, the result would be following:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 580px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/14f1744547a102e86e28533e30002439/b6272/screen3.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.24324324324324%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 3\"\n        title=\"Screen 3\"\n        src=\"/static/14f1744547a102e86e28533e30002439/b6272/screen3.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/14f1744547a102e86e28533e30002439/12f09/screen3.png 148w,\n/static/14f1744547a102e86e28533e30002439/e4a3f/screen3.png 295w,\n/static/14f1744547a102e86e28533e30002439/b6272/screen3.png 580w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 580px) 100vw, 580px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p>So what is happening?</p>\n<p>Function without the named parameters will be called like <code>cylinder(h = 2, r1 = 5, r2 = 1);</code>\nBecause <code>r2</code> is <code>1</code> by default when <code>r1</code> is defined. You can read more about this <a href=\"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/OpenSCAD_User_Manual/Primitive_Solids#cylinder\">here</a>.</p>\n<h1>Operations on shapes</h1>\n<p>With the help of documentation we can create 3d shapes like spheres, cubes etc. But what if we'd like to create some more complicated figures?\nWe need to wrap our figures with operation functions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>union</code> - sum</li>\n<li><code>difference</code> - subtraction</li>\n<li><code>intersection</code> - overlapping part of shapes</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So if you want to create crossed cubes, below you can find the way how you can do this:</p>\n<pre><code>union() {\n    cube(size=[2,2,10], center=true); //first cube\n    cube(size=[2,10,2], center=true); //second cube\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 480px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/b6dc48b7c8da5f581e8d57d054a71643/e85cb/screen4.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 82.43243243243244%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 4\"\n        title=\"Screen 4\"\n        src=\"/static/b6dc48b7c8da5f581e8d57d054a71643/e85cb/screen4.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/b6dc48b7c8da5f581e8d57d054a71643/12f09/screen4.png 148w,\n/static/b6dc48b7c8da5f581e8d57d054a71643/e4a3f/screen4.png 295w,\n/static/b6dc48b7c8da5f581e8d57d054a71643/e85cb/screen4.png 480w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p>Cube with gap in the middle:</p>\n<pre><code>difference() {\n    cube(size=[2,2,10], center=true); //first cube (base)\n    cube(size=[2,10,2], center=true); //second cube (will be subtracted)\n    //nth shape will be also subtracted from base\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 342px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/7b77611a92ad014b81863f686ffd6a2f/e2c15/screen5.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 153.3783783783784%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 5\"\n        title=\"Screen 5\"\n        src=\"/static/7b77611a92ad014b81863f686ffd6a2f/e2c15/screen5.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/7b77611a92ad014b81863f686ffd6a2f/12f09/screen5.png 148w,\n/static/7b77611a92ad014b81863f686ffd6a2f/e4a3f/screen5.png 295w,\n/static/7b77611a92ad014b81863f686ffd6a2f/e2c15/screen5.png 342w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 342px) 100vw, 342px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p>And... we've encountered a glitch here. We have a hole in the middle of our cube, but because the width of the first cube equals the width of the second cube, we have walls with width 0. In preview it may be a bit distracting, but if we render it (F6 or Design > Render) it should disappear.\nThe second way is to make subtracted shape a bit wider.</p>\n<pre><code>difference() {\n    cube(size=[2,2,10], center=true); //first cube (base)\n    cube(size=[2.01,10,2], center=true); //second cube (will be subtracted)\n    //nth shape will be also subtracted from the base\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>The common part of two cubes - should be cube with dimensions 2x2x2:</p>\n<pre><code>intersection() {\n    cube(size=[2,2,10], center=true);\n    cube(size=[2,10,2], center=true);\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 520px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/2e2edd77a556617a86b33d8935b6cccd/69902/screen6.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 102.02702702702702%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 6\"\n        title=\"Screen 6\"\n        src=\"/static/2e2edd77a556617a86b33d8935b6cccd/69902/screen6.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/2e2edd77a556617a86b33d8935b6cccd/12f09/screen6.png 148w,\n/static/2e2edd77a556617a86b33d8935b6cccd/e4a3f/screen6.png 295w,\n/static/2e2edd77a556617a86b33d8935b6cccd/69902/screen6.png 520w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 520px) 100vw, 520px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p>It is possible to wrap operations in operations. For example, at first <code>rotate</code> cube and then subtract it from another one.</p>\n<pre><code>difference() {\n    cube(size=[2,2,10], center=true);\n    rotate([45,0,0]) cube(size=[2.01,10,2], center=true);\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 258px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/fedf82c88ee5198b72f0500cd6ea7ba4/d9489/screen7.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 238.51351351351352%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 7\"\n        title=\"Screen 7\"\n        src=\"/static/fedf82c88ee5198b72f0500cd6ea7ba4/d9489/screen7.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/fedf82c88ee5198b72f0500cd6ea7ba4/12f09/screen7.png 148w,\n/static/fedf82c88ee5198b72f0500cd6ea7ba4/d9489/screen7.png 258w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 258px) 100vw, 258px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p>There can be a useful debug function. Just put hash <code>#</code> before the operation:</p>\n<pre><code>difference() {\n    cube(size=[2,2,10], center=true);\n    #rotate([45,0,0]) cube(size=[2.01,10,2], center=true);\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 546px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/4d272a9e8eec3edc124285c68bfcc871/76aed/screen8.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 106.75675675675676%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 8\"\n        title=\"Screen 8\"\n        src=\"/static/4d272a9e8eec3edc124285c68bfcc871/76aed/screen8.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/4d272a9e8eec3edc124285c68bfcc871/12f09/screen8.png 148w,\n/static/4d272a9e8eec3edc124285c68bfcc871/e4a3f/screen8.png 295w,\n/static/4d272a9e8eec3edc124285c68bfcc871/76aed/screen8.png 546w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 546px) 100vw, 546px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<p>Feel free to try other operations and transformations.</p>\n<h1>Another basic useful stuff</h1>\n<h2>Conditional rendering</h2>\n<p>Sometimes we want to render something only in certain cases. OpenSCAD allows us to use <code>if</code> and it has a similar syntax to javascript etc.</p>\n<pre><code>a = 1;\nif (a > 0) {\n    sphere(r=a);\n}\n</code></pre>\n<h2>For loop</h2>\n<p>Syntax:\n<code>for(variable = [start : increment : end]) {}</code>\nLet's create holes around cylinder's border.</p>\n<pre><code>radius=5;\n\ndifference() {\n    cylinder(h=1, r=radius, center=true);\n\n    for(i=[0:360/6:360]) {\n        echo(i);\n        rotate([0,0,i])\n            translate([radius-1,0,0])\n            cube(size=[1,1,1.1], center=true);\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/7b784559ddce8985a2b962f4836efa7f/0a47e/screen9.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 93.24324324324323%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen 9\"\n        title=\"Screen 9\"\n        src=\"/static/7b784559ddce8985a2b962f4836efa7f/fcda8/screen9.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/7b784559ddce8985a2b962f4836efa7f/12f09/screen9.png 148w,\n/static/7b784559ddce8985a2b962f4836efa7f/e4a3f/screen9.png 295w,\n/static/7b784559ddce8985a2b962f4836efa7f/fcda8/screen9.png 590w,\n/static/7b784559ddce8985a2b962f4836efa7f/0a47e/screen9.png 600w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image}</p>\n<h2>And others...</h2>\n<p><code>echo</code> is useful for debugging.\nI often use also <code>import</code> for importing external <code>stl</code> files to the project.\nOpenSCAD has a lot of popular mathematical functions and transformations.\nIt also allows us to create 2d models and extrude it to 3d models with <code>linear_extrude</code> or <code>rotate_extrude</code>. You can look for details <a href=\"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/OpenSCAD_User_Manual/2D_to_3D_Extrusion\">here</a>.\nDocumentation is very easy to use so I believe this doesn't need any further explaining.</p>\n<h1>Last words</h1>\n<p>OpenSCAD is a very powerful tool if we know how to use it. I was able to create useable models in a few hours after reading the manual. If you are a developer and prefer writing a code to drawing, I think it will be perfect for you.</p>","excerpt":"As a developer, 3d modeling was something that I had always wanted to try since it was something that I needed to visualize the final…","frontmatter":{"slug":null,"title":"3d modeling as a developer","description":null,"author":"pawel","tags":["3d modeling","CAD","OpenSCAD"],"date":"2017-10-15T22:00:00.000Z","image":null},"timeToRead":5,"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/new-www/new-www/src/mdData/blog/2017-10-16-3d-modeling-as-a-developer.md"},"site":{"siteMetadata":{"siteUrl":"https://brightinventions.pl"}}},"pageContext":{"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/new-www/new-www/src/mdData/blog/2017-10-16-3d-modeling-as-a-developer.md"}},"staticQueryHashes":["2189233960","3181594896"]}